<TITLE> US to form import safety panel </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 WASHINGTON, July 18 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - The United States is forming an import safety panel to report to President George W Bush in 60 days following a string of incidents that have raised questions about the safety of products from China, an administration official said on Wednesday. The creation of the new panel, to be headed by Health and Human Services Secretary Michael Leavitt, is expected to be announced later on Wednesday. In one of the latest incidents that has prompted calls in Congress for the administration to step up efforts to keep out harmful imports, the US Food and Drug Administration in late June said it would hold imports of Chinese farm-raised catfish, shrimp and other seafood until suppliers prove they are free of harmful residues. That followed a recall of more than 1 million Chinese-manufactured toy trains on June 13 because some may have contained lead paint. Earlier this year, melamine, a chemical used in plastics and fertilizers, surfaced in pet food from China, killing animals and prompting wide recalls. A poisonous chemical often found in solvents and antifreeze was recently detected in some Chinese-made toothpaste. Sen. Dick Durbin, a Illinois Democrat, has proposed slapping a fee on all foreign food imports to give the U.S. Food and Drug Administration resources to expand inspections. Sen. Charles Schumer, a New York Democrat, has demanded the Bush administration appoint an "import czar" to protect consumers against potentially harmful Chinese impor
